      "content": "Mortgage statements can be confusing, but don't worry, it's a common thing! In the early years of your loan, a larger chunk of that $2100 payment goes toward interest, which is how the bank makes its money. As time goes on, more of your payment starts chipping away at the actual principal balance. You'll see a noticeable shift, much like how a small, persistent stream of water slowly wears down a large boulder, but the boulder is the principal, and the stream is your monthly payment!\n\nTo give you the exact breakdown for Year 5 versus Year 25, I would need the original loan amount, as the principal portion changes based on the starting debt. However, I can tell you the general trend: in year 5, you'll still be paying a significant amount to interest, but by year 25, the interest portion will be significantly smaller, and the principal payment will be much larger.\n\nThink of it like this: when you first start, you're paying the \"entrance fee\" to the loan (interest), and later on, you're focused on actually owning the house (principal). If you're looking at a loan with a",
